GIT STASH & POP 
    git stash is used as a temporary storage box for your changes, this can be used in situation where you are half way through something and someone ask if you can quickily go in to said branch and you dont want to commit that branch so you can just temporarly store it.
        - [git stash] this command hides away all your uncommited changes think of it sort of like hitting a pause button.
        - [git stash list] this command displays all your stashes or any work you have sttashed away.
        - [git stash apply] this command takes changes you previouley saved with git stash and reapplies them in your working directory. this command is super useful if you want keep reusing this in other directorys.
        - [git stash pop] this command applies the most recent stash to your working directory and removes that stash from the stash list. this is useful  when you are done with it and want to keep things clean.
        - use case: These commands are especially handy when you need to switch context quickly—like jumping between branches or tasks. Maybe a teammate asks for a quick hotfix on main, or you want to pull the latest changes before continuing your work. Instead of committing unfinished code, you can stash your changes, switch over, and then bring everything back later with a pop.
        
        It’s one of those moments where Git can feel a bit rigid—you’re not ready to commit yet, but you still need to move fast. Stashing gives you a way around that: save your progress temporarily, switch contexts, and then return to your work as if nothing interrupted you.

    RESET, REVERT AND CHERRY PICK
        
        - [git revert] - this command undoes a previous commit by creating a new commit, it doesnt erease history its takes changes introduced in commit <a1b2c3d> and creates a new commit that does the opposite and is safe to use in shared branches and production.
        - [git reset] is a more aggressive command it essentially moves the branch pointer backwards, there are three types of git reset soft, mixed and hard
        the soft moves your pointer back but keeps changes staged. mixed version moves the pointer and also unstaged your changes. and the hard version which should be approached with caustion litrally nukes everything as it rewrites the history and can be dangerous in production.
        - [ gity cherry pick] this command allows you to take a specific commit from another branch somewhere else and apply it in your current one. which can be quite useful for hot fixes  for exam,ple you fix a bug in the main and you want to pull that single commit into your release and you dont want to merge everything you just want that single commit this command will allow you to cherry pick that.

        QUICK SUMMARY: Use `revert` when you need to safely undo changes on a shared branch. Use `reset` when you want to move your local history backward. And use `cherry-pick` when you need to grab a specific commit from another branch without merging everything. These are powerful tools, and once you understand when to use each one, your Git workflow becomes much more efficient.
    
